ar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr\n| yAxisTitle = No. of new cases\n| legend     = Legend\n| y1         = 0, 1, 1, 3, 4, 7, 7, 6, 6, 25, 31, 22, 25, 48, 109, 85, 67, 110, 205, 124, 158, 114, 126, 185, 291, 259, 373, 262, 160, 184, 307, 281, 269\n| y1Title    = New cases per day\n| yGrid      = \n| xGrid      = \n}}</div>\n''* Laboratory-proven COVID-19 disease as reported by regional hygiene stations and laboratories''\n\n<div class=\"toccolours\" style=\"width:800px; margin:1em 0 1em 0\">\n<center>'''New confirmed recovered and deaths per day'''</center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type=rect\n| linewidth=1\n| showSymbols=1\n| width=600\n| colors=green,black\n| showValues=\n| legend     = Legend\n| xAxisTitle=Date\n| xAxisAngle=-45\n| x=16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr,\n| yAxisTitle=New counts per day\n| y1Title= Recovered\n| y1= 3, 0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, 3, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 14, 20, 16, 10,\n| y2Title= Deaths\n| y2= 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 2, 7, 0, 2, 4, 6, 6, 7, 7, 3,\t\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}</div>\n\n==Epidemic curve==\n\n===Flattening the curve===\n[[File:Covid-19-curves-graphic-social-v3.gif|thumb|upright=1.6|An illustration of the effect of spreading out infections over a long period of time on healthcare capacity managing patient volumes, known as flattening the curve<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiles |first1=Siouxsie |title=The three phases of Covid-19 \u2013 and how we can make it manageable |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/09-03-2020/the-three-phases-of-covid-19-and-how-we-can-make-it-manageable/ |website=The Spinoff |accessdate=9 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>]]\n\nThe main priority of affected nations currently is to move to a slower doubling time of new cases, to ensure less crowded hospitals and therefore a lower case fatality rate.<ref name=\"who.int\">https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/managing-epidemics-interactive.pdf</ref><ref>https://www.seznamzpravy.cz/clanek/v-italii-umira-uz-8-nakazenych-proc-je-smrtnost-dvakrat-vetsi-nez-v-cine-93717</ref>\n\nGovernments of different countries take different approaches to flatten the epidemic curve. Beside travel bans and isolation of complete communities, citizens are also often requested to stay at home and keep [[Social distancing|social distance]].<ref name=\"who.int\"/>\n\nResearch indicates that measures must be applied rigorously and immediately in order to be effective. Also, the national community's commitment to supporting/tolerating the restrictions and following the advice of health authorities plays an important role in the success of flattening the epidemic curve and limiting the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Maharaj |first1=Savi |last2=Kleczkowski |first2=Adam |title=Controlling epidemic spread by social distancing: Do it well or not at all |journal=BMC Public Health |date=20 August 2012 |volume=12 |pages=679 |doi=10.1186/1471-2458-12-679 |pmid=22905965 |pmc=3563464}}</ref><ref>https://medium.com/@tomaspueyo/coronavirus-the-hammer-and-the-dance-be9337092b56</ref>\n\nFor example, in South Korea mass testing efforts were successful. The South Korean national testing capacity reached 15,000 tests per day. Compared to population size, the Czech Republic reached the same rate of testing on 23 March 2020. The Ministry of Interior in South Korea also rolled out a smartphone app that can track the quarantined and collect data on symptoms, so scientists are able to see more epidemiological data.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Normile |first1=Dennis |title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success? |journal=Science |date=17 March 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abb7566}}</ref>\n\n===Curve comparison===\n[[File:Epidemic curve COVID19 certain countries.jpg|400 px|left]]\n\nComparing cumulative numbers of confirmed cases in selected countries, including the Czech Republic, shows the different curves of the epidemic in different countries.<ref name=\"datawrapper.de\">{{cite web|url=https://www.datawrapper.de/_/Sgf7v/|title=COVID19 Epidemic curve selected countries|last=|first=|date=|website=datawrapper.dwcdn.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>https://onemocneni-aktualne.mzcr.cz/covid-19</ref> The chart shows the number of known cases and the pace at which the number increases on a logarithmic scale. The actual number of people infected may be and likely is, significantly higher, as only cases where the virus was confirmed by laboratory testing are shown. Many cases may only have an asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic course of the disease and never seek treatment. In yet others, the infection may still be in the incubation period, when it is asymptomatic and may not yet be detectable even by testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2020/03/200309110456.htm|title=COVID-19 infections in U.S. may be much higher, new estimates show|last=|first=|date=|website=sciencedaily.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Basic reproduction number==\nIn epidemiology, [[Basic reproduction number|the basic reproduction number]] (sometimes called basic reproductive ratio, or incorrectly basic reproductive rate, and denoted R<sub>0</sub>, pronounced R nought or R zero<ref>Milligan, Gregg N.; Barrett, Alan D. T. (2015). Vaccinology: an essential guide. Chichester, West Sussex: Wiley Blackwell. p. 310. {{ISBN|978-1-118-63652-7}}. OCLC 881386962</ref>) of infection can be thought of as the expected number of cases directly generated by one case in a population where all individuals are susceptible to infection.<ref>Christophe Fraser; Christl A. Donnelly; Simon Cauchemez; et al. (June 19, 2009). \"Pandemic Potential of a Strain of [[Influenza]] A (H1N1): Early Findings\". Science. 324 (5934): 1557\u20131561. Bibcode:2009Sci...324.1557F. doi:10.1126/science.1176062. PMC 3735127. {{PMID|19433588}}.</ref> The definition describes the state where no other individuals are infected or immunized (naturally or through vaccination).\n\nThe higher the R ratio number, the faster the disease spreads. If R is less than one, the reproduction within the population decreases.<ref>https://www.seznamzpravy.cz/sekce/koronavirus-stopcovid</ref><ref>https://oxfordmedicine.com/view/10.1093/med/9780199596614.001.0001/med-9780199596614-chapter-6</ref>\n\n<div class=\"toccolours\" style=\"width:1000px; margin:1em 0 1em 0\"><center>'''Development of R ratio in the Czech Republic'''</center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type       = line\n|linewidth  = 2\n|showSymbols= 1\n|width      = 850\n|colors     = #F46D43, #A50026, #C4ADA0, #C4ADB0, #C4ADC0\n|showValues =\n|xAxisTitle = Date\n|xAxisAngle = 45\n|x          = 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr,\n|yAxisTitle = \n|legend     = Legend\n|interpolate= monotone\n|yAxisMin   = 0\n|y1         = 2.47, 2.3, 2.1, 2, 2.3, 2, 1.9, 1.6, 1.5, 1.6, 1.7, 1.5, 1.6, 1.5, 1.4, 1.4, 1.4, 1.3, 1.2,\n|y1Title    = Daily R ratio \n|y2         = 0.58, 0.29, 0.17, 0.24, 0.37, 0.16, 0.18, 0.11, 0.11, 0.14, 0.20, 0.15, 0.18, 0.11, 0.06, 0.07, 0.10, 0.08,0.07\n|y2Title    = New cases ratio \n|yGrid      =\n|xGrid      =\n}}</div>\n\n\nDuring the second half of March 2020 the progress of the pandemic in the Czech Republic showed a decrease in the R<sub>0</sub> ratio from the value above 2.0 down to the value 1.5 or below. The day-to-day ratio of the total number of cases decreased in a similar way, falling below 10 percent at the end of March.\n\nWhile the basic reproduction number does not show how serious the situation ''is'' (in absolute or per capita numbers), it gives an idea of how it is ''likely to develop''.{{cn}}\n\n==Case details==\n\nDetailed information was reported regarding most of the first 99 cases, up to 12 March 2020:\n{| role=\"presentation\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|+ <strong>Case details</strong>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Case no.\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Date announced\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Status\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Origin type\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Origin\n! colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Location\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Treatment facility\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Sex\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Age\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Nationality\n|-\n! City\n! Region\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''1'''<ref name=\"case1-3\"/>\n| 1 March 2020\n| {{Partial failure|Confirmed}}\n| {{Success|Travel-related}}\n| {{flag|Italy}}, [[Udine]]\n| [[Prague]]\n| [[Prague]]\n| {{Success|Home isolation}}\n| Male\n| 67\n| {{flag|CZE}}\n|- class=\"expand-child\"\n| colspan=\"10\" | A Czech man born in 1952 had attended a conference in [[Udine]], [[Italy]]. He has contacted Czech authorities already on 26 February. After returning from Italy he had stayed in home quarantine and it was found one of his Italian colleagues was confirmed COVID-19 positive. After his condition worsened he went to the Infection Clinic at Bulovka Hospital. The test proved to be positive on 1 March. He is a teacher at the [[Czech University of Life Sciences Prague]].<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/02/world/europe/02reuters-health-coronavirus-czech.html|title=Czech Republic Cancels Flights, Bars Fans From Races Over Coronavirus|date=2020-03-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The patient has moved from [[Bulovka Hospital]] to home quarantine on 9 March 2020.<ref name=\"mar09.BulovkaRelease\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''2'''<ref name=\"case1-3\"/>\n| 1 March 2020\n| {{Partial failure|Confirmed}}\n| {{Success|Travel-related}}\n| {{flag|Italy}}, [[Milan]]\n| [[Prague]]\n| [[Prague]]\n| {{Partial failure|[[Bulovka Hospital]], [[Prague]]}}\n| Female\n| ~20\n| {{flag|USA}}\n|- class=\"expand-child\"\n| colspan=\"10\" | A young woman from the US, born 1999, studying in Milan travelled to Prague through Vienna, Budapest and Brno. Feeling sick she visited the Emergency room at [[Motol University Hospital]] where she was handled as potentially infectious and moved to [[Bulovka Hospital]].\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''3'''<ref name=\"case1-3\"/>\n| 1 March 2020\n| {{Partial failure|Confirmed}}\n| {{Success|Travel-related}}\n| {{flag|Italy}}, [[Auronzo di Cadore]]\n| [[D\u011b\u010d\u00edn]]\n| [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]]\n| {{Success|Home isolation}}\n| Male\n| ~43\n| {{flag|CZE}}\n|- class=\"expand-child\"\n| colspan=\"10\" | A man born in 1976 from [[D\u011b\u010d\u00edn]] had been skiing with his family in Italy and after returning to the Czech Republic, his wife took him to a hospital in [[Usti nad Labem]] on Saturday 29 February9, he was positively tested and afterwards transferred from Masaryk Hospital, [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem]] to [[Bulovka Hospital]] in [[Prague]]. The rest of his family had no symptoms and remained in home quarantine pending further COVID-19 tests. The patient moved from [[Bulovka Hospital]] to home quarantine on 9 March 2020.<ref name=\"mar09.BulovkaRelease\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''4'''<ref name=\"case4\"/>\n| 2 March 2020\n| {{Partial failure|Confirmed}}\n| {{Success|Travel-related}}\n| {{flag|Italy}}, [[Auronzo di Cadore]]\n| [[D\u011b\u010d\u00edn]]\n| [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]]\n| {{Partial failure|Masaryk Hospital, [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem]]}}\n| Female\n| 53\n| {{flag|CZE}}\n|- class=\"expand-child\"\n| colspan=\"10\" | A Czech woman was holidaying in the Alps, staying in the